<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="840" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d840">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">Department of the Army Files:
                                    Telegram</note>
                                <head>No. 840<lb/><hi rend="italic">The Chief of the Military
                                        Representation on the Allied Control Commission for
                                        Rumania</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SBGCTVR1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schuyler</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">War
                                        Department</gloss></hi></head>
                                <opener>
                                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract<note n="1" xml:id="d840fn1">For the full text of this message, see <ref target="#d812">document No. 812</ref>.</note>]</seg>
                                </opener>
                                <opener>
                                    <seg rendition="#left"><hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                                        <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi></seg>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Bucharest</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-24">24 July
                                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p><gloss target="#t_M1">M</gloss> 1285. …</p>
                                <p>1. Under Article 7<note n="2" xml:id="d840fn2">Of the armistice
                                        with Rumania signed at Moscow, September 12, 1944 (Executive
                                        Agreement Series No. 490; 59 <gloss target="#t_Stat1">Stat</gloss>. (2) 1712).</note> the <gloss target="#t_ACC1">ACC</gloss> has required the delivery to
                                    Russia as “<gloss target="#t_War1">War</gloss> Booty” of
                                    considerable quantities of industrial equipment including oil
                                    pipe, tubing and casing, on the ground that such equipment
                                    originated in Germany. I propose to protest that [<hi rend="italic">the</hi>] application of this policy to any
                                    industrial equipment, regardless of its <pb facs="0937" n="743" xml:id="pg_743"/> origin, which can be shown to have been
                                    actually purchased and paid for prior to 23 August 1944.<note n="3" xml:id="d840fn3">i. e., before the surrender of
                                        Rumania.</note> I am informed that a similar protest has
                                    been made to the Soviet Government by the US Ambassador in
                                        Moscow.<note n="4" xml:id="d840fn4"><persName corresp="#p_HWA2">W. Averell Harriman</persName>. See
                                            <ref target="frus1945Berlinv01#d323">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, document No.
                                        323</ref>.</note></p>
                                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>